title: Hungarian National Tourist/Trade Information Office
description:
Hungarian National Tourist Office was set up on 1 st March 1994 to carry out public interest tourism marketing tasks for the Ministry of Economic Affairs, Department of Tourism Policy. Its company form is a one-person share company with its own capital of 15 million HUF. It has been carrying out the national tourism marketing activity since 13 October 1995, on the basis of a contract signed with the Hungarian Tourist Board, predecessor of the Department of Tourism Policy of the MEA from 1 November 1995, on commission. 
Hungarian National Tourist Office provides basic and comprehensive information on the country's natural beauties, historic monuments, culture, gastronomy and all other aspects of potential interest to tourists. In addition, the provision of information comprises the full range of Hungarian tourism services, helping to bring demand and supply together and boost tourism receipts.


Hungarian National Tourist/Trade Information Office

description: A fantastic little curry house - the New York Times recently rated it one of the best curry houses in London at its price point. title: Ukai Sushi
description:
This is quite an unusual restaurant in that it isn't a noodle place with the odd sushi dish on the side - it really does specialise exclusively in sushi!  Ukai is a smart sushi restaurant, which originated in 2006 in Portobello Road, and became so poplar that it almost immediately opened another branch in nearby Westbourne Grove.  Lavender Hill is the third branch, opening in November 2008.  

http://www.ukai.co.uk/

title: Cake Boutique
description:
Cake Boutique is a  coffee shop on the Lavender Hill specialising in interesting cakes and pastries.  The rage is impressive - everything from toffee apples and apple strudel to fig tarts and interestingly coloured cupcakes.  Also serves all the coffees and drinks you'd expect.  A couple of years back, this shop front used to be a rather scruffy furniture depot - you wouldn't recognise it now that it's become a very smart shop - lots of red, white and marble.  They also have pavement seating, as well as small tables for children, and free wi-fi.  Service was friendly and, al in all, it's quite a find for this part of the Lavender Hill and worth a visit.  
http://thelondoncakeboutique.co.uk/

title: LHP Lavender
description:
Heating & Plumbing merchants - a plumbers shop from the old school, which has clearly been in business for many years.  It's unusual in that almost everything is served from behind a counter: you ask, they go and rummage around, often balancing precariously to get to things on upper shelves.  This is an old fashioned shop format that was widespread until about the 1960s but is now rarely seen in the UK (another example is the builders' merchants two doors down the road).  One benefit of this format is that as things don't have to be particularly clearly or well laid out, they can fit a surprisingly wide stock in a small high street shop unit with only two floors.  When it comes to plumbing and heating, and this is a useful shop to have nearby.  

2 Queenstown Road, London SW8 3RX.  Tel 020 7622 8768.

http://www.visitlondon.com/attractions/detail/64208
